**Problem 10**

Next we perform a more thorough comparison between direct uniform quantization and compressed signal uniform quantization. First we plot the probability distribution of the random variable input signal.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Next we plot the output of both the uniform quantizer of Y (top graphs) and the compressed signal (Z) uniform quantization (bottom graphs). The following are raw signal plots and we show them for all levels 2..1024.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

An important pattern we can see here from the comparison is that the quantization of the compressed signal is better than the former. This is likely because the inherent distribution of the signal is exponential which means most of its values are near zero as can be seen by the histogram of problem 3. This means that many of our quantile intervals are not being used in a standard uniform quantizer. It would be more efficient to use more intervals are lower values and less at high values. This demonstrates the effectiveness of nonuniform quantization in such a scenario.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

**Conclusion**

It can be concluded that not all signals are created equal. Especially though with random exponential distributions, as they tend to have more low value components than high values, this lends to a different kind of quantization scheme. That is, nonuniform quantization, which can be achieved by passing the input signal through a nonlinear system that reduces its dynamic range.
